<HEAD>CNN Book Tells All on Turner and Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH HASTINGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Edward Turner III, a.k.a. ``Terrible
Ted,'' ``Mouth of the South'' and ``Captain Outrageous,'' is short
on words and long on bravado.
   Even when someone is writing a book about his baby, the Cable
News Network.
   ``Ted's out there,'' said author Hank Whittemore, in what may be
one of the understatements of the decade. ``He's like a brief
tornado in your life.''
   Whittemore has written ``CNN: The Inside Story,'' a 308-page
chronicle of the little network that could. Its release Friday by
Little, Brown &amp; Co., coincides with CNN's 10th birthday.
   Excerpts have appeared in TV Guide. Some of the stories in the
book have been told more times in more journalistic watering holes
than Dan Rather's infamous seven-minute stroll off a live CBS
newscast.
   Take, for example, the time a light bulb exploded in the CNN
Washington bureau and ignited the clothing of on-camera reporter Dan
Schorr. Or the time weatherman Stu Siroka was victimized by the
Chromakey process, which allows one picture to be placed behind
another. All viewers saw was Siroka's bald head, suspended above the
weather map.
   Take Turner, who after agreeing to cooperate with Whittemore,
would walk in to scheduled interviews and say ``Hi, Hank, how much
time you want? I've got about nine minutes.''
   Whittemore spent six months interviewing present and former CNN
movers and shakers. His account tells a spirited and sometimes
bizarre tale of how Turner, equipped with $100 million and even more
chutzpah, screamed, bullied, sued, cajoled and bankrolled his way
into television history by launching the first 24-hour all-news
network.
   On cable.
   And here is Whittemore, the author a best seller called ``The
Super Cops,'' magazine articles and television documentaries, on a
nationwide tour to promote his book and calling from a pay phone in
Washington's National airport.
   Asked to explain Turner, Whittemore pauses. There was an awards
dinner in Kansas City that Whittemore attended recently. ``Now I'm
still working on the book,'' Whittemore recounted, ``and he comes up
to me and says `What are you going to write about me? Just don't
make me out to be an ass.'
   ``Then he looks around and kind of beams, and says `Well, maybe I
was.'
   ``I felt like I was in a Harold Robbins novel,'' Whittemore says,
and laughs.
   ``The man will say the most outrageous things and you wonder `Is
the man just not thinking or is he being very calculating?' ''
   Whittemore talked not only to Turner. He spent hours with Ted
Kavanau, an early CNN executive who became president of Headline
News only to be forced out, and Reese Schonfeld, the network's
founding president, who also left, as well as former anchor Mary
Alice Williams, now with NBC, and several others.
   ``CNN: The Inside Story'' begins in a dilapidated white clapboard
house that was the network's first home and ends in the megalomaniac
structure in Atlanta that now houses the international news agency.
   It copiously notes many weird tales of the upstart network, from
the early days when work crews were literally finishing the set as
anchor Bernard Shaw read the news.
   And the time a cleaning woman, not knowing Shaw was on live,
walked right up to his desk and emptied his trash basket, and the
time a reporter said that ``Mary Ass Williams'' was standing by, and
yet another instance when a correspondent reported that scientists
were trying to grow ``genetically engineered orgasms'' in the
laboratory.
   But gaffes are not the only events noted. Loud and clear,
Whittemore's book comes through with the underlying theme that CNN
made television history by making the Big Three sit up and take
notice.
   And by making CBS, NBC and ABC reluctantly admit they were no
longer the only games in town.
   Round-the-clock news coverage gave CNN a number of firsts:
   President Reagan walking into a Washington, D.C., hospital after
being shot; a split-screen of the hostages being released in Iran as
Reagan was sworn into office, and a lonely cameraman perched atop a
cherry-picker with the only live feed of a nuclear warhead being
removed after an Air Force explosion in Arkansas.
   ``It seems to me that what they want to do is wire the entire
world,'' Whittemore said. ``They want to be totally global, in terms
of sending and receiving signals so that you get what Turner calls
the world talking to itself.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>

