<HEAD>``CBS Evening News'' Third in Ratings by Narrow Margin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The once-dominant ``CBS Evening News,'' now
trailing ABC's ``World News Tonight'' in ratings, was third last
week, national audience estimates showed Tuesday.
   ABC's newscast, anchored by Peter Jennings, easily won the week
ending Jan. 14 with a ratings average of 11.9. It was the 12th time
this season the program has triumphed over CBS's newscast,
according to an ABC spokesman.
   Tom Brokaw's ``NBC Nightly News,'' which usually is in third
place, was second in ratings last week with a 10.9 average, edging
out Rather's newscast, which was third by a narrow margin of
one-tenth of a ratings point.
   Acording to the A.C. Nielsen Co., each ratings point represents
921,000 homes.
   CBS officials had no immediate explanation for Rather's
third-place finish, which last happened in the final week of
December, according to CBS.
   Last week, one major CBS affiliate, KPIX-TV in San Francisco,
shifted Rather's program to an earlier 5:30 p.m. PST start time.
   But it isn't known yet if that was a factor in the week's
Nielsen returns for the program, said Michael Eisenberg, CBS vice
president for audience measurement.
   ``We couldn't point to that as the only reason right now,'' he
said in an interview Tuesday. ``We're studying the matter and
trying to find out what the reasons are.''
   In a news conference in Los Angeles over the weekend, Rather
said, ``I intend to keep right on keeping on. It's true, the `CBS
Evening News' is a work in progress ... we're constantly trying to
improve.''
   Asked about his delivery of the news from a standing position,
the anchorman said, ``I've always wanted to stand and do the
broadcast. I don't think that's cosmetic.''
   Rather and CBS News President David Burke said they were unable
to explain the ratings tumble.
   But each discounted speculation that some of it was due to
Rather's much-publicized on-air confrontation with then GOP
presidential candidate George Bush during a ``CBS Evening News''
interview in early 1988.
   Burke blamed part of the program's ratings slide on what he
called statistical errors in the Nielsen ratings system and on the
programs of other broadcast outlets such as the 24-hour Cable News
Network.
   ``There is increasing competition from CNN, which means you
don't have to make an appointment to watch the news anymore, you
have it on all the time, and I think they do a fine job,'' Burke
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

