<HEAD>HBO's Shows Dominate Cable Television's ACE Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   HBO's ``Murderers Among Us: The Simon
Wiesenthal Story'' won four awards, including best movie or
miniseries, as Home Box Office continued its winning streak in
cable television's ACE Awards.
   HBO captured 31 ACE awards, 14 during a live telecast Sunday and
17 at a dinner Friday, nearly matching its 1989 harvest of 35
awards.
   CNN won the Golden ACE Award for its coverage of the upheaval in
China last May. ``The Ray Bradbury Theater'' won four awards,
including best drama series.
   Showtime, A&amp;E and CNN each received six awards as a record 19
cable networks picked up honors from the National Academy of Cable
Programming.
   In addition to the Golden ACE, awards in 26 categories were
handed out Sunday night at the 11th-annual presentations.
   Awards in 56 categories, largely in the crafts, were presented
Friday.
   Other winning networks included USA Network with five awards,
ESPN four, TNT, TBS, Discovery and Disney three each, Nick at Nite,
Bravo and MTV two each, Madison Square Garden, Family Channel, TNN,
SET, Lifetime and VH-1 one apiece.
   Twelve cable networks televised the ceremony, which featured
hosts Dinah Shore, Joe Namath, Paul Reiser of NBC's ``My Two
Dads,'' and Julie Brown of MTV's ``Just Say Julie.''
   ``Murderers Among Us,'' which chronicled the life of
concentration-camp-survivor-turned Nazi-hunter Simon Wiesenthal,
was cited for best movie or miniseries, directing, editing and art
direction.
   ``Ray Bradbury Theater'' won for best actor in a drama series
for Harold Gould and for art direction and costume design.
   Showtime's ``It's Garry Shandling's Show'' won best comedy
series and for directing and writing a comedy series.
   Ruben Blades won as best actor in a movie or miniseries for
``HBO Showcase: Dead Man Out.'' Vanessa Redgrave won as best
actress for TNT's ``A Man For All Seasons.''
   Mark McKinney won as best actor in a comedy series for HBO's
``The Kids in the Hall.'' Lucy Webb won as best actress in a comedy
series for HBO's ``Not Necessarily the News.''
   The ACE for best newscaster went to CNN's Bernard Shaw for
``Bernard Shaw's Coverage of China.''
   HBO's ``Tales From the Crypt'' and Showtime's ``Gloria Estefan &amp;
Miami Sound Machine,'' won three each.
   The best comedy special was won by HBO's ``One Night Stand: Dom
Irrera.'' Bill Maher was cited as best performer in a comedy
special for HBO's ``One Night Stand: Bill Maher.''
   HBO's ``The Magic Circus: Cirque Du Soleil'' won as best variety
special or series. A&amp;E's ``Stage: Jacques Loussier: Bach to Bach''
was named best international music special or series.
   HBO's ``You Don't Have To Die'' won for best documentary
special, and the network's ``HBO Showcase: Lip Service'' won for
best dramatic special.
   Other winners include: Sydney Walsh as best actress in a
dramatic series for HBO's ``Vietnam War Story: `Dirty Work;'''
James Whitmore as best supporting actor in a movie or miniseries
for HBO's ``Glory! Glory!;'' Mimi Maynard as best supporting
actress in the same category for ``The Forgotten'' on USA Network;
Billy Crystal, Whoopi Goldberg and Robin Williams as best
entertainment hosts for HBO's ``Comic Relief III;'' Larry King as
best program interviewer for CNN's ``Larry King Live.''
   A&amp;E's ``Sweet As You Are'' won as best international dramatic
special or movie. The ACE for best international theatrical special
or series went to A&amp;E's ``Stage: The Rivals.'' MTV's
``Rockumentary'' was cited as best documentary series and ``New
Visions'' on MTV's VH-1 was picked as best music series. Bruce
Springsteen won as best performer in a music special or series for
HBO's ``HBO World Stage: The Human Rights Now Tour.''
